      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with frictional contact and bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity for Ti-6Al-4V is an accepted model form for pedicle screw compression-bending; supported by literature precedent.",
      "rationale": "The model employs continuum solid elements with bilinear isotropic hardening (E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus 1.2 GPa) for Ti-6Al-4V, consistent with published FDA and industry FEA practices for spinal implant simulation. Frictional contact (mu=0.2) at screw-rod interface captures load transfer mechanism. Model form is well-established for this class of problem. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from ASTM F136 coupon testing on same material lot; geometric inputs from CMM measurements of production screws.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties were characterized from tensile coupon specimens machined from the same material lot as the test constructs, per ASTM E8. Geometric inputs (screw OD, thread pitch, rod diameter) were measured by CMM on five production screws per lot. Input uncertainty was propagated through the model using a one-at-a-time sensitivity study. Achieved level meets required level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
